<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18440819-2216">
               <interp inst="t18440819-2216" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18440819"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18440819-2216" type="date" value="18440819"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440819-2216-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2216-18440819 t18440819-2216-offence-1 t18440819-2216-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2216. <persName id="def1-2216-18440819" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2216-18440819" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2216-18440819" type="surname" value="SCOTT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2216-18440819" type="given" value="FRANCIS THOMAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">FRANCIS THOMAS SCOTT</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440819-2216-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2216-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="kill"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440819-2216-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="manslaughter"></interp> for feloniously killing and slaying <persName id="t18440819-name-1521" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1521" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1521" type="surname" value="READ"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1521" type="given" value="JOHN SAMUEL"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18440819-2216-offence-1 t18440819-name-1521"></join>John Samuel Read</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution</hi>,</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1522" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1522" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1522" type="surname" value="KELLY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1522" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KELLY</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 15th of July I was in the Blackfriars-road—I saw the prisoner riding down the New-cut—I was about crossing over to the other side—I cried out, seeing a man crossing just at the moment that the prisoner was up to him—I also heard the prisoner cry out after me—he was riding at a very rapid rate indeed, galloping and urging on the horse, beating it on the side of its flank with his hand—I saw nothing in his hand—he had a spur on—he was quite near to the man when I hallooed out—the man was crossing from Rowland Hill's chapel—there was plenty of time for the prisoner to pull up—there was no traffic of carts at the time—he could have seen the man—the deceased had got about half-way across the road—I ran as fast as I could, not knowing which way he would turn, and by the time I got across he was up opposite me, or very near me—I saw him knocked down by the horse.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was there a lad with the old man? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I did not see whether he ran away, I was rather confused at the time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1523" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1523" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1523" type="surname" value="KNOX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1523" type="given" value="SUSANNAH MARY"></interp>SUSANNAH MARY KNOX</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 15th of July I saw the prisoner in the New-cut, coming across to Charlotte-street, riding at a very furious rate—I saw him urge on the horse with his right hand—he applied his spur, and likewise beat the horse with his right hand—I saw him some</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184408190233"></xptr>
               <p>time before I saw the deceased—the deceased was crossing from Rowland Hill's chapel, across Charlotte-street, when he was knocked down—I heard Kelly cry out three times—when I first heard Kelly cry out the deceased was not far from the horse's head—he had not time to get out of the way of it—I do not know which way the child who was with him escaped, but I think Kelly's hallooing made the child let go the father's hand.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you see the deceased's hat blow off? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, when he was close to the horse's shoulder—I was looking straight up the New Cut—the prisoner was coming towards me, and towards the deceased—he took his spur off afterwards.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1524" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1524" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1524" type="surname" value="READ"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1524" type="given" value="JAMES THOMAS"></interp>JAMES THOMAS READ</persName>
                  </hi>. I was with my father, John Samuel Read, on the 15th of July, crossing from Rowland Hill's chapel across Charlotte-street—the prisoner was just going to knock my father down when I first saw him—I was by Rowland Hill's chapel when I first heard Kelly cry out—I only heard him call out once—I did not hear the prisoner call out—I was behind my father when he was knocked down—I did not cross with my father—I stopped to look at some sheep which were going down Blackfriars-road.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you hear the prisoner halloo out? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, just as he was going to knock my father down—my father's hat blew off, and instead of turning after me he stooped to pick it up—he was in the road when his bat blew off—I was on the pavement—when he stooped to pick up his hat the horse jumped over him, and kicked out his hind legs, and struck him on the head.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were the lambs between you and your father in the road? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, they were just behind my father in the Blackfriar's-road—they had not come up to my father—they were going in the same direction—they were not against the prisoner—my father's side was towards the horse—it was a regular crossing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1525" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1525" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1525" type="surname" value="CLARK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1525" type="given" value="FREDERICK LE GROS"></interp>FREDERICK LE GROS CLARK</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant surgeon at St. Thomas's Hospital. On the 15th of July, Read was brought into the hospital perfectly insensible—the cause of death was extravasation of blood into and upon the surface of the brain—I inquired into the nature of the accident—the blow and concussion that he received were the cause of death—the appearances were such as were likely to have been produced by the accident described—there was a small scalp wound which was trivial, but there was extravasation of blood sufficient to cause death.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Suppose the horse to have cleared him by jumping, was the blow on the head likely to have been the effect of a kick from the horse's heel? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Very likely.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1526" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1526" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1526" type="surname" value="COWLING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1526" type="given" value="THOMAS ROBERT"></interp>THOMAS ROBERT COWLING</persName>
                  </hi>. I was driving my own omnibus this day from Kennington-gate to the Angel at Islington—I saw the prisoner on horse<lb></lb>back—there are four roads meet at the spot described—I saw the deceased and the little boy about the centre of the road, in the carriage way, and the prisoner coming along out of Great Charlotte-street to go into Little Char<lb></lb>lotte-street—he was in a condition to see the deceased before he called out—he called out twice—he pulled up sufficient to have cleared the deceased if he had not turned, but his hat blew off, and he stooped—the boy ran back again to the pavement—while the deceased was stooping the shoulder of the horse struck him in the side, which knocked him down—I did not see whether the horse kicked him or trod upon him—the prisoner was travelling a gentle canter, at the rate of seven or eight miles an hour—he certainly was not galloping furiously.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you speak of the centre of the road do you</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184408190234"></xptr>
               <p>mean the centre of the crossing? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—there is a crossing, but the deceased was not on it—he was by the side of it, more remote from the pri<lb></lb>soner—I was about twenty yards off when I heard the call out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1527" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1527" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1527" type="surname" value="BLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1527" type="given" value="GUSTAVUS WILLIAM"></interp>GUSTAVUS WILLIAM BLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a consulting surgeon. I am not at all acquainted with the prisoner or his friends—Cowling told me the prisoner was to be tried for manslaughter—I said perhaps it was important for him to have as many witnesses as he could, and as a matter of justice I had no ob<lb></lb>jection to state what I knew—I was riding upon the box of Cowling's omni<lb></lb>bus this day with the driver—we were going very slowly, and were very close to Great Charlotte-street—I saw the prisoner coming along on horseback, at the rate of seven or eight miles an hour—the horse lifted his feet very high, and made a great noise, something like what they call a butcher's trot—when about half way across Black friars-road the prisoner hallooed out—the deceased was passing along from Rowland Hill's chapel, as if going along Blackfriars-road towards the Surrey gate—he was not going along the crossing that is used there—he was further in Little Charlotte-street—the boy was with him—they made a movement to cross before the horse, after the prisoner had called out—I did not notice the deceased's hat fall off, but he seemed to make a halt and hesitation, and turned round—the little boy ran back, leaving him in the road, and it was then that he was struck by the horse's shoulder—the prisoner was not beating or spurring the horse at that time that I saw—he checked when he hallooed out—he might have stopped the horse entirely, but I considered at the time it was the deceased's hesitation, and turning round in the road which caused the coalition—I should say the prisoner pulled up his horse within six yards of the deceased from the place where he was struck—he turned back of his own accord, and rode back to the accident, and then the omnibus I was on drove on—I had no idea the coalition would have killed the deceased—he was not thrown forcibly on the ground, but made a rotary motion, and then fell—I do not think there was any kick, as from the position of the parties, if there had been, it would have been at the lower part of the man, not his head—I did not observe anything furious in the prisoner's driving—it was not a place which was likely to be dangerous—I consider he gave sufficient warning, that if there bad been more persons on the crossing they might have got out of the way.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. O'BRIEN</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You could only see him when he came on the road? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, I saw him about ten yards before that—whether he was spurring or whipping his horse previous to that, I do not know—I heard the prisoner halloo out twice at least—I did not hear any one halloo out previous to him—I did not hear persons cry out after the accident, "Stop him"—I was in a condition to have heard it—I will not say no one did cry out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1528" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1528" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1528" type="surname" value="KELLY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1528" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KELLY</persName>
                  </hi>. I wish to correct this gentleman's statement; it was two men that ran from each side of the road that stopped the horse—it was at least sixty yards from the place. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> It is utterly false—there was not a person so situated that they could stop him—there was only one person went after him, and he did not reach him before he turned back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440819-name-1529" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1529" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1529" type="surname" value="LITTLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-name-1529" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM LITTLE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a farrier, and live in King-street, Lambeth. I know the horse the prisoner was riding on that day—it is an old horse—I should say it was not capable of going at any extravagant rate—he would go at the rate of six or seven miles an hour—one of his fore legs is a stiff leg—he cannot bend it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18440819-2216-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18440819-2216-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440819-2216-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value=""></interp>NOT GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
